'''''Culture of death''''' has two distinct meanings:
*A term coined by [[John Paul II]]. It is used in contemporary [[Political discourse analysis|political discourse]] in many countries, including the [[United States]] and [[Poland]], to describe supportive positions on certain subjects, such as [[abortion]], [[euthanasia]], [[human cloning]] and [[capital punishment]] which adherents of opposing positions deem to be inconsitent with their concept of a "[[culture of life]]".

*A term used in [[Imperialism|Colonial Europe]] to describe [[barbarian|"barbaric"]] cultures which allegedly glorified or worshipped death. This was then used as a justification for the subjugation and colonization of these cultures.

